to LLC after getting a mortgage?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Technically, transferring property to an LLC after closing triggers the \"due-on-sale\" clause in your mortgage, allowing the lender to demand full repayment. In practice, most lenders don't enforce this clause as long as you continue making payments\u2014they care about getting paid, not who owns the LLC. However, there's no guarantee they won't enforce it. Some investors proceed with the transfer and accept the small risk. Others refinance into a commercial loan in the LLC's name. Discuss with your lender before transferring."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "How much does it cost to set up and maintain an LLC?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "LLC formation costs vary by state but typically range from modest filing fees for DIY online formation to higher costs if using an attorney (recommended for proper protection). Add attorney fees for operating agreement drafting. Annual maintenance includes state renewal fees, registered agent fees if using a service, and potential franchise taxes depending on your state. California, for example, has minimum annual franchise tax. While LLCs aren't expensive, factor these costs into your investment analysis."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What's Next in Your Journey?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Ready to find and analyze properties with proper protection planning? These guides help:"}}]};
